segments.text: the minority started developing a fairly strong political say and their feeling was you're trying to break up this little political concentration of power we're getting the traumatic thing was when I had to debate on television with this man who had threatened the lives of major HUD officials and debate the plan but because we understood that you don't dictate local policy from Washington you know to
local government in Texas, we had structured a program that basically allowed more options without requiring a whole bunch of things.
Basically, we said, first of all, you find housing for everybody.
Then you worry about letting people live exactly where they want to.
And those that want to should be able to move.
And those that don't want to shouldn't have to.
Was there a perception, too, that they wanted the Allen Parkway for the expansion of the CBD?
Alan Parkway really wasn't involved in any of this.
It wasn't even an issue.
I see.
The issue, at least from Washington, was how do you disperse people?
And Alan Parkway at that time was a given, and our bottom line was there simply didn't begin to be enough public housing.
So debating, closing one down, just simply wasn't an issue.
What year was this?
This was, I believe, in 79 and 80.
maybe 88 and 1.
This was part of the whole federal concept of regional fair share in housing.
Yeah.
They called it the Regional Housing Mobility Program.
And those were the old days of the area wide housing opportunity plans where you would tell a community how many units they were going to take and so forth.
Yeah, it was an attempt to homogenize the entire region.
Or an attempt to get the region operating as a whole.
We never wound up, though we discussed at length, the idea of doing one of these plans.
We decided that that was not in the best interests of this particular area.
Political dynamism.
Exactly, exactly.
And there were no guarantees that, in fact, you would get this extra money.
Yeah, in fact, several COGs found themselves threatened with nonexistence if they went ahead with such a program.

That was one of the times I felt very proud of the way we pursued something because there was some interest stirred up by outsiders in our doing it because some of the small communities perceived they might get some more money.
And I went to Washington.
We developed a great many materials.
I just said, okay, here are the facts.
You know, we're not going to suggest how you decide this, but here are the pros, here are the cons, here's the way it would work.
And we had really quite a large public debate.
We had several different public hearings and public meetings where we had officials from HUD down and just answered questions.
And all of this took place well before any kind of a decision needed to be made.
And the final decision was that this was not something to pursue at this time.
At any rate, what it- There was no mandate for HUD to do it.
No, they would have liked to, but they
They talked about a mandate, and then for all practical purposes, HUD went away as far as regional councils were concerned.
When they stopped giving 701 money, that was sort of the end of it.
Nor took you long nor long.
Exactly.
In my mind, that was then the beginning of the growth of regional councils in terms of HGAC, which is sort of the only one I can speak to.
Because when there was no longer federal money that suggested you do this program or that program, the programs then had to be structured by what the board was willing to put local money in.
And so then the local money started going to address things that they saw as problems, particularly problems that were interjurisdictional.
I think the high point of the evolution of this was the solid waste, the regional solid waste plan that we did.
One of our county judges came to the board one day, and he said, we have a real problem in solid waste.
City of Houston's contract is trying to put a landfill in our community.
We don't have a place to put our own garbage daily.
I am inundated by salesmen of different technologies, and I don't even know how to evaluate those technologies.
I have a feeling waste to energy might be a good idea.
I don't even know how to begin to go about it, evaluating whether it's a good idea.
HGAC, you need to do something.
It took us probably close to a year working with a committee of the board, all elected officials, to decide what would be the appropriate thing to do.
And all along, as I'd work with this subcommittee, I would say, well, we need to do this plan.
Uh-uh, we don't want a plan.
Doris, forget about a plan.
We don't want a plan.
Well, then I got smarter.
We all learn over the years.
And I said, what we need is an action guide.

We need an action guide for solid waste so that I'd say, now, do you think we ought to survey all the communities and do some research and figure out what the problems are in the different parts of the region?
Definitely.
I said, and you do want to know what technologies are available and what the advantages and disadvantages of each are.
Definitely want that.
And then you kind of want us to do some forecasts, analyze what the problems are now versus what they're likely to be and when.
Oh, definitely.
And I think you want us to make some recommendations as to actions that need to be taken.
I said, yeah, they want to.
I said, well, that sounds like an action guide to me.
And so the board then.
Pretty sneaky.
Well, you know, hey.
You got to do what you got to do.
If you have one bad word, it may not be the concept that's bad.
It may be the word.
And that's what it turned out to be.
They liked everything about it, but they didn't want to call it a plan.
Then we went to individual governments.
We wrote all of the governments a letter asking if they would be willing to put up a donation, voluntary contribution towards this plan.
We gathered, I think, 35 or 40,000 dollars.
And the council of governments added another, it wound up being about another $100,000 in order to develop this plan.
Because it was something that the governments, they perceived that they needed this.
Sure.
Those that had the garbage had nowhere to put it.
Those that didn't have it were receiving it.
They didn't know what the future would hold.
And it's the first time I would probably say that I was involved in a planning process where there was consistent interest on the part of elected officials.

Several times when I gave presentations on the status of the planning program, and you couldn't avoid giving technical presentations showing them how we developed these little computer programs that would project landfill needs by acre and so forth.
Never have I seen elected officials be interested
in a technical.
I was able to maintain their interest with presentations of technical material I wouldn't even present to them.
But there was a sense that they should be part of this all the way through.
When we finished, we took some brave stands.
We said urban areas should not have landfills.
The board went on record as saying that they favored waste to energy as the best way of
taking care of solid waste.
During the course of the study, the state legislature passed then House Bill 1719, which called for local and regional planning in solid waste management.

The legislature then never funded the legislation, but it allowed, it put a little teeth into a plan because it allowed it to go through an approval process, which once approved, local actions would have to conform to it.
Oh, yeah.
The State Department of Health, of course, couldn't get around to writing regulations.
And as long as we were doing this plan and getting a lot of support locally, we decided, well, it ought to be approved at the state.
So we got together a committee from several COGs and wrote the regulations for them.
And to date, have the only approved regional solid waste management plan in the state of Texas.
It was a true plan in the sense of planning.
We projected, we made service areas, we made recommendations for each area.
It was extremely well received.
And I believe that's because this was a local problem, identified locally, involved elected officials and the public very early on in the process.
Financially committed.
Committed local money.
And the plan as it emerged was a true plan, but it was also a plan that understood the local processes.
So, as I said, I've seen a total evolution.
Shortly after the initial completion of the plan, when we were just looking into some implementation actions that the college should take, our recommendations were three levels.
to the state, a level of regional recommendations with the largely additional studies that needed to be performed, and recommendations to the various units of government.
And in a regional sense, our service areas were interjurisdictional.
We totally ignored jurisdictional lines because the concept was that cities and counties have to work together in this area.
And we made recommendations to each area.

as we were beginning to proceed with implementing the regional portion of this, and I might add that there have been quite a number of local actions on the part of Houston as well as some of the surrounding areas since the adoption of the plan towards implementing it.
At any rate... Who adopted the plan?
The HSE Board of Directors, and then they sent it through all the mechanisms, and it was approved by the state of Texas and the Department of Health.
Did the local units of government...
We didn't ask them to individually adopt the plan.
And some of it was because the nature of the state legislation, you couldn't use one of our service areas for a local planning effort, because the local planning effort had to be only a jurisdiction.
You know what sometimes happens where a law is so specific as to defeat its own purpose.
At any rate, shortly after its completion, and in fact,

week that HGAC was honored locally for winning a planning award from Texas APA for the plan, the announcement was made that the comptroller at HGAC had embezzled just about all of the agency's money, which started a new phase for the Regional Council and that was
Oh, I guess a little less than a year and a half ago.
What was the month and date on that?
It was December 1985 that it was discovered.
And what was discovered was that it had gone back over a period of seven years.
And it was probably the final number, which will never be known, was probably close to $2 million.
We did better than that a day back.
We had a $3.5 million loss.
Did you have FBI agents in your office the next morning?
We had them around the agency.
No one ever came to my office, so I never even knew what they looked like.
As it turned out, it was not federal funds that were involved, except for a very, very small amount.
But the money was all pulled out using the administrative charges or indirect.
all wound up being local money, which was just about all the money the COG had that they could spend in any discretionary way.
As a result of that, any programs using local funding were automatically cut out of the budget.
The COG had to borrow $800,000 just to survive.
And so any local money that was coming in from dues and from the state was then used towards retiring the debt.
And that effectively... Well, most of your programs did require local matching funds.
Well, there was enough money set aside for matches.
But the department that I had kind of created, which was really a true planning department, had very little outside funding.
We received a water quality planning grant from the state
very small community development grant, $25,000 to $30,000.
And I guess as much as $300,000 a year, maybe a little more, was local money that was being used to support innovative programs.
We developed a regional information service with a very nice demographics program, which not only served the local governments, but served the private sector as well.
We were doing just a broad range of programs
that were being funded locally.
Well, all that money was effectively gone.
As you know... What happened to him?
Well, he pled guilty to over a million dollars theft, and he is now in federal prison.
Along with... What was his name?
Bill Prince.
One of his staff spent six months in federal prison.
Another member of the administration was
indicted and pled guilty and got probation, several others on whom it was thought that charges would be filed.
Charges just weren't filed.
I believe that the US Attorney's Office gave immunity in return for information.
But that was not.
It took, as you can imagine, the better part of a year till the legal aspects of that were put away.
And then the COG got very involved
preparing lawsuits against the bank that cashed hundreds of thousand dollars in forged checks.
And the auditor, who was the auditor for the prior four years, and told the board of directors at their last report how proud they should be of how well managed the money was.
So that took a lot of attention.
Who was the auditing firm?
Ernst & Winning, one of the big eight firms.
At any rate,
waited for some of that to die down.
And of course, any of the staff could not very well leave the agency until all investigation was complete.
But it became obvious that we had come full circle.
And the programs for the next, I would say, at least five years will be the very basic programs that have outside funding.
And there wouldn't be an opportunity in the near term for the kinds of innovative or
true planning work that we were doing.
So as you know three months ago I tendered my resignation and am now operating as an independent consultant.
I'm sure that affected the careers of quite a few people in terms of shifts or new opportunities and possibly a shift in terms of
as you've already suggested, the centers of activity of the professional staff.

I think, too, although my department was most profoundly affected financially, and we immediately, within the course of the year, lost three positions, and a fourth one was jeopardized, and that was at the staff of eight or nine.
But it affected others in that the transportation manager, who was a
and has a national reputation, had only been there two years, left over a controversial issue in a plan.
The COG was in a position, in my opinion, where it couldn't handle any more controversy.
Couldn't handle headlines.
There had been a real loss of credibility.
And whereas before the scandal, they would have taken on the issue and stood up for what
you know, they felt was the proper planning perspective.
I think at the time, they just couldn't do that.
I can understand that, because the executive committee of our general assembly decided that after the theft of the $3.5 million by our Tom Cruax, that they had to take things easy and were unwilling
to become involved in any kind of innovative programs whatsoever, and sort of relaxed in the position of being kind of a information center for the region.
Well, there seems to me to be a concern about taking on anything controversial.
And there isn't even money to be an information center, because that was being locally funded.
So I don't know what
there's going to be now the best funded program at the COG is the Jobs Training Partnership Act.
And though it's being administered by a COG, it isn't a planning program in any sense of the word.
So I see the agency moving a lot more towards direct service, provision of service type programs, and away from planning.
Interestingly, when they advertised the job, one of the qualifications as far as education was,
a degree in planning or a number of things, or a degree in business.
So it's a totally different perspective now, I believe.
Then it makes one wonder about the future of regional planning in Texas.
Yes, that's true because there are 24 councils of government in Texas.
The state is quite supportive of them.
I mean, it's legislated.
The boundaries are legislated.
The state provides a planning grant each year.
But there are problems in many of them.
They're either not well enough funded or politically they're not well enough accepted.
Or they lack professional leadership.
There are not a whole lot of professional planners in the regional planning agencies.
Now when I left, I had been for several years the only member of AICP that was on the staff.
Shortly before I left, I did hire another certified planner.
Who was that?
Jeff Table.
And he's now, as far as I know, the only member of AICP on the staff.
One of my former students.
That's right, and a very fine young player.
Is he AICP now?
Good for him.
Well, North Central Texas Cog has a good reputation.
Yes, and they do some good work, and they're well-funded.
I think one of the differences is my perception is that they are not quite as political.
They work a lot more with, say, the city managers where we worked with the mayors.
And I think that makes a difference, so that they're able to stay more in the technical arena, where we were more in the political arena.
However, we probably make bigger strides in forming public policy.
They have a very well-organized police training.
Yes, HGAC does that as well.
Do they?
But to me, that's, again, a kind of a service function rather than a planning function.
And it worries me when we talk about the shift of activities of councils of government away from planning.
to providing service activities, which tend, in my mind, to become nothing more than busy work.
Well, it's different.
It's administration.
And that's not what planning is.
Unfortunately, in this country, in the late 1980s, planning is still, as a profession, not
proven itself in some way.
And when there isn't federal support for planning, which there hasn't been for quite some years now.
Since Nixon.
Exactly.
You're unlikely to see the kinds of good planning that we used to see.
It still tends to be a way of justifying for a government to do what they're going to do anyway.
It tends to take place not by planners,
I've been, since I've been in private practice, interested that every engineer calls themselves a planner.
Every economist calls themselves a planner.
I don't call myself an economist or an engineer.
Well, if planning is so unpopular politically, I think it's all the more remarkable that they do so.
That engineers and architects always seem to call themselves planners.

Because everyone acknowledges there's a component that has to be the plan, but that's because you need that component to justify spending a lot of money on capital improvements, rather than before you think of spending the money, you know that you have to think this through and what it's going to mean to the future and what's needed and where it's needed.
There's a tendency for everyone to think that they can do that.
It makes me wonder, too, if...

The members of APA, as we now know it, are going to continue to push for registration of the title and practice of planning as being a professional activity rather than considering planning in its generic form.
I haven't heard a whole lot about that in recent years, but I would like certainly to see it.
All anyone seems to need to do to be a planner is to go to a few meetings.
Interestingly, you know, I was in China last fall as part of a delegation of urban planners, and the thing that struck me the most about the difference in planning was we presented
oh, the environmental review process, and how you go about historic preservation from a process perspective, an economic development process.
And they presented projects to us.
And I think we're always fighting.
We feel that we've evolved into a process, which is what true planning is.
And yet, that seems to still be the battle.
Is planning something you do to allow a project to continue?
Or is it an ongoing process that helps you to deal with all the issues
of an urban society.
How do you feel we've evolved in which one of those ways?
Well, I think that we view it, planners see the process and seem to understand this as an ongoing process and it doesn't shock them that you have to update your forecast annually.
A lot of the politicians and a lot of public service people in other areas still see it as the project.
develop a new water source, you're going to have to have something you call the plan that says, do it.
Yeah, you're saying that planters really have learned how to deal with change.
I think they have, but I don't think they've instructed the others or the public.
Well, of course, this used to be the role of ASPO before we amalgamated with them and to try to educate the lay planters.
And this is one of the reasons that I felt it was important in 1970 to have a short course for planning commissioners, which then, a few years later, I felt we should expand to public officials.
And that, I think, has done some good in Texas.
It has.
And I think what you just said is what's significant.
Planning officials sometimes understand, but it's the other public officials.
Your public works director doesn't understand.
No.
And the elected officials?
No, they don't.
It's not politically comfortable, because one of the reasons solid waste is such an issue is that it's an issue that requires long-range planning.
It takes many years to implement a proper solid waste project.
It isn't politically feasible for anyone that's elected to office to bring up the subject.
And no one, well, I won't say no one, very few are willing
to put their careers on the line for a project that isn't going to be up and running for 10 or 20 years.
And so they avoid the issue.
And yes, they avoid the issue.
And frequently, there were hearings on the community development program for small cities.
One of the commissioners who has since resigned, but didn't run again from Harris County,
testified.
And he said, Harris County is not eligible for this program.
We're an entitlement community.

But I want to encourage having this program and doing, you know, giving the money out on a regional basis because, he says, I have to recognize as a commissioner in Harris County that it's because of Houston and Harris County that many of these small communities are having the problems they're having.
our enormous growth has spread these problems, and it's incumbent on us to at least support any way that they can have relief from these problems.
And that was a very forward-thinking view, but he was, not by profession, he's a political scientist, but he understood what you try to do with planning.
Sure, sure.
Well, Doris, thanks very much for your inputs, and you'll be getting a transcription
to review and comment on so you'll have your chance then to add anything or make any corrections that are needed.
Well, I enjoyed it.
I hope it didn't end my career.
Thank you.
